Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

---

## API Inventory

| API | Location | .NET 8 Status |
|-----|----------|---------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), throws only on `WaitSleepJoin` state |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** (`SYSLIB0006`) |

## Bugs in the Original Code

1. **Race condition** — Multiple `Enqueue()` calls before `RunLoop` processes → `Reset()` clears the signal but only one `Dequeue()` runs, losing items until the next `Set()`
2. **Empty queue crash** — `Dequeue()` on an empty queue throws `InvalidOperationException`
3. **Unhandled exception** — `Thread.Interrupt` throws `ThreadInterruptedException`, which is never caught in `RunLoop`, so the thread crashes uncleanly

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new(false);
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wait for either a new event OR cancellation
            WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            // Drain all queued items (fixes the original race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }

            _newEvent.Reset();
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();              // signals token.WaitHandle, wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);        // wait up to 5s for clean exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter weight; same semantics |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancellation token wakes `WaitAny` cooperatively |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed entirely | Loop exits via `IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative cancellation at loop boundary |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation |
| Single `Dequeue()` | Drain loop | Fixes race where multiple enqueues were lost |

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Don't replace `Thread.Abort` with `Environment.Exit` or `Process.Kill`** — these kill the entire process, not just the thread.
2. **`CancellationToken` won't interrupt `Handle(item)`** — if `Handle` is long-running, pass the token into it and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe points inside.
3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable`; leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The `IDisposable` pattern on the class handles this.
4. **Reset after drain, not before** — calling `_newEvent.Reset()` before draining (as the original did) loses signals from concurrent `Enqueue` calls.
